    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/4c14a5dcf2ce4f5a9c03728d5c03ccd4",
      "title": "Complexity science informed approaches to health policy, systems and service research [BUR 24-04]",
      "content": "<p><u>Background</u>: Progress in achieving health outcomes, and more specifically health equity, has stalled. ‘Magic bullet’ interventions, services or policies which are easy to define, implement and one-size-fits-all are a thing of the past. Today’s health systems are highly complex, shaped by diverse agents with varied constraints and interests, spanning local to global levels. Complexity science views health systems as inherently complex, operating through nonlinear dynamics. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><u>Aim</u>: In this PhD, you will focus on a health topic and use complexity science informed approaches such as group model building, systems dynamics modeling, agent-based modeling, and network analysis to assess potential impacts of solutions.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><u>Supervisors</u>: Dr. Karin Diaconu (<a href=\"mailto:KDiaconu@qmu.ac.uk\">KDiaconu@qmu.ac.uk</a>); access to network of complexity science experts</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/7c5ba12a500646eabaae4541748d7ca2",
      "title": "Identity, peacebuilding and psychosocial wellbeing in post-conflict settings [BUR 24-05]",
      "content": "<p><u>Background</u>: Identity and identity politics have been at the core of many conflicts globally, with significant psychosocial, socioeconomic, and sociopolitical impacts on affected populations that influence overall wellbeing and functioning. The proposed PhD project aims to examine the link between identity, peacebuilding, and psychosocial wellbeing by analyzing people's responses to these challenges in post-conflict settings.  </p>\n<p><u>Aim</u>: To understand definitions of identity, impacts of conflict on identity, responses to associated psychosocial challenges, and whether/how post-conflict experiences enable peacebuilding.</p>\n<p><u>Supervisors</u>: Dr. Arek Dakessian (<a href=\"mailto:ADakessian@qmu.ac.uk\">ADakessian@qmu.ac.uk</a>); Dr. Yasin Duman (<a href=\"mailto:YDuman@qmu.ac.uk\">YDuman1@qmu.ac.uk</a>)</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/855a79e3a3e145d5985be71c61dd6763",
      "title": "Refugee healthcare integration with national health systems  [BUR 24-06]",
      "content": "<p><u>Background</u>: As displacement becomes prolonged, there are growing calls for integration of refugee healthcare into national health systems as a sustainable approach benefiting both refugees and hosts.  </p>\n<p><u>Aim</u>: To better understand how integration of refugee healthcare within national systems can be successfully achieved, with different theoretical and methodological focus (resilience, health system/HSS, governance, financing and cost-effectiveness, etc.) as well as geographical scope depending on the applicant skills, experience, and interest.</p>\n<p><u>Supervisors</u>: Dr. Ibrahim Bou Orm (<a href=\"mailto:IBouOrm@qmu.ac.uk\">IBouOrm@qmu.ac.uk</a>); Dr. Marcia Vera Espinoza (<a href=\"mailto:MVeraEspinoza@qmu.ac.uk\">MVeraEspinoza@qmu.ac.uk</a>): Dr. Sophie Witter (<a href=\"mailto:SWitter@qmu.ac.uk\">SWitter@qmu.ac.uk</a>)</p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/c88357456ae6443494e38c623fa07ecc",
      "title": "Advancing MHPSS theory and practice in fragile and/or protracted crisis settings [BUR 24-07]",
      "content": "<p><u>Background</u>: This topic has three possible foci:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Research that explores and advances the understanding of the role of culture and/or faith norms, beliefs and practices in mental health and MHPSS among understudied groups.</li>\n<li>Research that explores and advances theory and/or practice related to the integration of protection and MHPSS in general or specifically the reintegration and rehabilitation of CAAFAG (children affected by armed forces and armed groups) among understudied groups in post-conflict / protracted crisis settings.</li>\n<li>Research that explores and advances theory and/or practice related to the mainstreaming or integration of MHPSS with other sectoral programmes, particularly livelihoods, climate resilience or health. </li>\n</ul>\n<p><u>Aim</u>: Explore and advance theory/practice in above MHPSS research gaps among understudied groups in post-conflict/protracted crises. </p>\n<p> </p>\n<p><u>Supervisor</u>: Dr. Kathleen Rutledge (<a href=\"mailto:KRutledge@qmu.ac.uk\">KRutledge@qmu.ac.uk</a>)</p>\n<p> </p>"
    },
    {
      "contentTypeKey": "216ea22b-01af-4645-8972-5766bbd75b6c",
      "udi": "umb://element/b84658e39de5489681f0ae610e0ea19e",
      "title": "The Impact of Climate Change on Health System and Community Resilience [BUR 24-08]",
      "content": "<p><u>Background</u>: Climate change poses major health threats, requiring urgent action to strengthen health and community resilience against impacts on infrastructure and empowering relationships.</p>\n<p><u>Aim</u>: Examine climate impacts on health/community resilience; identify interventions to bolster equitable, sustainable resilience.</p>\n<p><u>Supervisors</u>: Dr. Paul Kadetz (<a href=\"mailto:PKadetz@qmu.ac.uk\">PKadetz@qmu.ac.uk</a>); Dr. Karin Diaconu (<a href=\"mailto:KDiaconu@qmu.ac.uk\">KDiaconu@qmu.ac.uk</a>)</p>"
    }
